Java 7 Features:
  1. Try-With-Resources (Java 7)-  Automatically closes resources (like files, DB connections)  
      ❌ Old Way:
          BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"));
          try {
              br.readLine();
          } finally {
              br.close();
          }
      ✅ New Way:
          try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"))) {
              br.readLine();
          }
      Why needed:
          Avoid memory leaks
          Automatic resource management
          Cleaner code
      Important Rule :Resource must implement: AutoCloseable

 2.Multiple Catch - Handle multiple exceptions in one catch block
   ❌ Before
          try {
              // code
          } catch (IOException e) {
          } catch (SQLException e) {
          }
  ✅ After
        try {
            // code
        } catch (IOException | SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    Why needed?
        Reduce duplication
        Cleaner exception handling
  Important Rules-  Exceptions must NOT have parent-child relation
  ❌ Invalid:  
      catch (Exception | IOException e) // ❌
      Variable is implicitly final
      e = new Exception(); // ❌ not allowed

3.Diamond Operator-  Used for type inference in generics
    ❌ Old Way (Java 6)
        List<String> list = new ArrayList<String>(); Type repeated twice 
    ✅ New Way (Java 7+)
        List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(); -> Compiler automatically infers type
   How it Works:  Compiler reads left-hand side (LHS)
             List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(); Infers: ArrayList<String>
    ✔ Advantages:
        Removes redundancy
        Cleaner code
        Less error-prone
     Limitations:
        ❌ Cannot use without type context- new ArrayList<>(); // ❌ error (no LHS)
        ❌ Not allowed in method parameters (Java 7)- void test(ArrayList<> list) {} // ❌
        ❌ With anonymous class (Java 7)- new ArrayList<>() { }; // ❌ (Java 7)

