Virtual threads:
  Virtual threads are arguably the most significant addition to Java since Lambda expressions. 
  Introduced in Java 21, they allow you to run millions of concurrent tasks without the massive memory overhead of traditional Operating System (OS) threads.
1. How to Implement (The Syntax)
There are three primary ways to create virtual threads depending on your use case.
A. Using the ExecutorService (Recommended for most apps)
      This is the cleanest way to run tasks. Unlike fixed thread pools, this executor creates a brand-new virtual thread for every single task and destroys it when finished. Do not pool virtual threads.
      +1 
      try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
          executor.submit(() -> {
              // Your I/O-bound code here (DB call, API call)
              System.out.println("Running in: " + Thread.currentThread());
          });
      } // Executor automatically waits for tasks to finish (AutoCloseable)
B. Using the Thread Builder (For more control)
      If you need to name the thread or set a custom inheritance policy:
      Thread vThread = Thread.ofVirtual()
          .name("worker-", 1)
          .start(() -> {
              System.out.println("Doing work...");
          });
C. Static Factory Method (Quick & Dirty)
      Thread.startVirtualThread(() -> {
          System.out.println("Hello from a lightweight thread!");
      });
2. Enabling in Spring Boot 3.2+
    Since you are working with AKS and microservices, you likely use Spring Boot.
    You don't need complex Java code to enable this; just one property:
    application.properties
    Properties
    spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true
 What this does:
    Configures Tomcat to use virtual threads for every incoming HTTP request.
    Configures TaskExecutors (for @Async) and TaskSchedulers (for @Scheduled) to use virtual threads.
    Effectively allows your service to handle thousands of concurrent requests with just a few megabytes of RAM.
3. Usage & Use Cases: When to go "Virtual"
    Virtual threads are not a magic "speed up" button for everything. They are designed for I/O-bound tasks, not CPU-bound tasks.
    I/O Bound (The Sweet Spot): Database queries, calling other microservices (REST/gRPC), file system operations. When a virtual thread "blocks" (waits for a response), it unmounts from the OS thread, allowing another virtual thread to take its place.
    CPU Bound (The Trap): If you are doing heavy math, image processing, or video encoding, virtual threads offer zero benefit and might even be slightly slower due to context-switching overhead. 
                        Use standard platform threads or Parallel Streams for these.
4. "Hidden" Pitfalls (The Gotchas)
To keep your AKS pods healthy, avoid these common mistakes:
A. Thread Pinning (The synchronized problem)
    If you use the synchronized keyword around a blocking operation (like a DB call), the virtual thread becomes "pinned" to the OS thread. 
    It cannot unmount, which defeats the entire purpose.
    Fix: Replace synchronized with java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock.
B. ThreadLocals
    Virtual threads are cheap and short-lived. If you store large objects in ThreadLocal, you might end up with millions of them in memory simultaneously, leading to an OutOfMemoryError.
    Fix: Use Scoped Values (another Java 21+ feature) if you just need to pass data down the call stack.
C. Don't Pool Them
    In the past, we used FixedThreadPool(200) to prevent the OS from crashing. With virtual threads, the limit is your Heap Memory, not the OS. Just create a new one for every task.
